ERIC LIDJI
Senior Staff Writer

‘The Old Lady of the Schenley’ ,

Though it was destroyed 30 years ago, Forbes
Field’s presence can still be felt in the area of
Oakland that is now Posvar Hall.

Go down there. Down the long corridor of
Posvar Hall you can find home plate laid into the tile.
Through the scratched Plexiglas cover you can see
the plate, tattered from cleats of numerous Hall-of-
Famers.

Go back outside. There is a line of brick in the
cement that demarcates the left-field wall. You can
follow it to a plaque of the exact spot where Bill
Mazeroski hit his historic World Series winning
home run in 1960. I

Cross the street and see the real beauty of what’s
left, the left-field wall. Behind the trees and the flag-
pole stands a part of a stadium once considered a
worldly marvel and the greatest in America. Feel that
old brick and rust posts, trace the numbers painted on
the wall that also watched Babe Ruth’s final home
run sail above.

This is the story of Forbes Field, and then Forbes
Quad, and now Posvar Hall. It is a microcosm of the
plight of the University throughout the last century.
How do you place a campus in the city and derive all
the benefits of a city, while at the same time remove
it from that city so that it is an entity all its own?

The answer, if there is one, is most certainly not
easy and is always controversial, and the story that
leads up to the University’s decisions in the late ‘50s
takes us all the way back to the turn of the 20th cen-

tury.

The Barney Dreyfus affair

In the early 1900s Barney Dreyfus was as vision-
ary as a baseball owner could ever expect to be.

By his 40th birthday, the Gerrnan-bom Jew ’had
already immigrated to America, owned two sports
teams, acquired a lasting friendship with Honus
Wagner, one of the" greatest second basemen
ever and, most importantly,
single-handedly invented the
World Series.

In 1899, Dreyfus
became the sole owner of
the Pirates when he left his
team of nine years, the
Louisville Colonels, with a boatload of dough and
some of his best players, and moved north to
Exposition Park on Pittsburgh’s North Shore.

In 1901 and 1902, his team was incredibly suc-
cessful, winning the pennant both times. When his
team did it again in 1903, he decided to up the stakes,
challenging the best team from the other baseball
league at time, the Boston Pilgrims of the new
American League. _

It was the first World Series.

And the Pirates lost.

But Dreyfus didn’t stop. In 1909, he decided to
build a new stadium for his team that would eclipse
anything this nation had ever seen in a sports facili-

