EDITORIAL

Americans must learn about Islam

Since the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks,
Americans have discovered that we know
little about the Islamic world and the
Middle East. Perhaps some of you don’t
even know why we are using the terms
Middle East and Islamic world separately.

Every night for years we’ve heard on
the evening news about something happen-
ing “over there.” But now that it’s hit home
we’re ﬁnding ourselves challenged when it
comes to answering why.

Pitt and other universities _,are doing
something to alleviate this lack of inforrna-
tion. According to the Dec. 2 Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette, Pitt and other schools are
adding several new courses "on the Islamic
world and the Middle East for the spring
semester.

For example, in the spring you can
now take Politics of the Contemporary
Middle East, which is cross-listed as HIST
1763, PS 1383 and JS 1383. Religion in
India 2'(I-HST 1758, RELGST 1510), a
course traditionally offered, focuses on the
Indian subcontinent, including Muslim
inﬂuences.

Several Jewish studies courses also
focus on Israel and the Middle East, and the
linguistics department even offers Arabic.

According to the Pittsburgh Post-
Gazette, the religious studies department is
considering adding a Koran as Literature
course to complement the already-popular
Bible as Literature.

A course on the Nationality Rooms,

focusing on the cultures the rooms repre-
sent, would also be valuable to add. This
course could give students a general under-
standing of many cultures that they would
not otherwise receive.

Our leaders continually emphasize to
us that we will be involved in the Islamic
world for a long time. To keep an informed
debate on this subject continuing,
Americans need to make an eﬁort to learn
more.- "
Students are in a privileged position as
our job, in essence, is to learn. We should
take advantage of this. Even if a course on
Islam ‘or the Middle East does not fulﬁll
any requirements for you, does not “count’ ’
if you will, you should still take it. It will
“count” in making you an informed person.

While the addition of some courses on
Islam and on the Middle East is a good
start, Pitt needs to add more. For example,
the Post-Gazette reports that West Virginia
University is adding 35 for next semester
alone. Pitt should make a comprehensive
effort to attract ‘faculty with expertise on
Islam and on the Middle East and add more
courses in this ﬁeld.

Pitt is renowned for its intemational
studies programs. Yet CAS students can
take very few international studies courses
to fulﬁll requirements, and business and
engineering students are required to take
even fewer. This should change. As our
society becomes more‘ international, so
should our education.

